The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric pond, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Batlló House, Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar form to a skeleton, the locals seized it "the house of the bones".
Its organic forms, its attractive colors, the innovative use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds the scales and all-present gently curved lines, all of which is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The cover of the house plays with onyric lines, delicate colors and textures extracted from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought order are observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is lit so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the twisting of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The waving wood copies the frames of the windows, the rocks, the decorations of the doors, the mirrors and the letters.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district in number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Joseph Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting at zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of several apartments, did not design it by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans for the project there were ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in Casa Batlló's proposals was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Mila and the Güell de Gaudí Park, where other parts of it are located.
Because of its organic form, the premises soon after its completion caught it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it the "house of drawers".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique system in the house for the central heating age with ventilation breathers and typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange to have a tilt of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the construction rules of the moment and did not allow themselves to be influenced by them.
Still, the construction was granted the corresponding permit from the beginning, although the data indicated in it on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, at its completion, the municipality was so affected by the result that it requested correction.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public wheel.
The arrangements never took place, on the contrary: only 15 days after the council's request, Joseph Batlló requested permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
On the second floor gallery there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted in breaking all right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of connection of space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white tiles and blues covering the inner courtyard and tragalluces.
The game with the two colors provides the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the beginning that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the House Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it was a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The entrance price to the monument is not insignificant, reaching EUR 16.50, although students, retirees and card holders get 20% discount.
The amount exceeds significantly the entry price of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
