More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
The fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, originally designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, to the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device has the approximate size of a bead box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička case and began to inform about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of invading their privacy.
"We are all trying to say that this is not a spy, but another way to reduce the possibility of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of monitoring devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that, in certain cases, you can abuse such devices, for example if you get into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we haven't met with such cases yet."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," added Pilin.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočová warns of the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will just take it away.
"Even younger children show great creativity when they deliberately lose certain things if they want to avoid controlling them."
"Before, the parents had enormous confidence in the mobiles, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bocková says.
In your opinion, it is questionable if such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check if the child carries any type of electronic device that can reveal its location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the tracking devices are being extended, they will also be searched for, as their sale will undoubtedly be carried out with great publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go a step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, add that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and persons, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can serve as a help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If it is damaged, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person concerned."
"The most expensive devices are integrated into a tilting meter, so if the person simply repatriates and becomes immobilized, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," Čech says.
In your opinion, a service of this kind can be obtained even with smart mobile phones with navigation, in which only a special software must be installed.
The problem with the current tracking units is that they are currently devices with a size similar to a belt box or smaller mobile phones.
