A longer index finger than the ant indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest index than the anal are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple proof of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, Professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles indicates.
During the 1994-2009 period, he followed up with a British counterpart of over 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index finger on the right hand shorter than the cancel.
They had the same likelihood of prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the missing finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60%, the reduction was 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined during the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knew the study, but that it does not appear to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer can be "demonstrated entirely".
