Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private enterprises.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively animated mood prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes to democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a 40 per cent reduction in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
He also grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the polls in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Approximately 44 per cent of respondents in the region were satisfied with the way democracy operates in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but significantly higher than 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis was probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Moreover, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and that it has been reduced again this year, up to 32 per cent.)
However, the state of mind varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
The good economic performances of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the polls began, the most surveyed in Latin America mentioned crime, instead of unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent said that either they or a close relative had been the victim of the crime in the past year, a figure that had been reduced since 38 per cent last year and was the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of the respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are essential for development, while only 56 per cent in 2007 (see Figure 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of those surveyed in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country with greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (compared to 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by the polls in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela bears such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
