Yesterday, the UN has proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GEI) to an amount nearly one third of the additional reduction that needs to be made to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is reflected in the whole of major concrete projects that the United Nations expects to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent pumps, which still monopolies between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact pumps or, better yet, electroluminescent diode pumps (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1,800 million tonnes of GEI (Gt) emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
The lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary automotive park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emission countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, an additional 5 Gt of this quantity should be reduced to stabilise, before 2020, the rise in temperatures in two centigrades to avoid being monitored.
In the incandescent pumps, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, that is, a 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluorinated pumps, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED pumps, energy consumption is reduced twice more.
The fluorinated pumps last between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED pumps, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent pump, allowing us to make an idea of the savings that could be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in one hundred countries.
These new pumps can also work with rehosts and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations regarding fluorinated pumps, since they contain mercury and should be eliminated as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluo-compact pumps, but the coal thermal plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is poured out with the incandescent pumps.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of this international programme to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billions of dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2,500 million.
