Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world has a significant impact on the prestige of the Department of State.
The scandal, therefore, affects both victims and "vertigos".
But we enter into the true nature of what has happened.
In ancient times, in Orwell’s day, it could be conceived to all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true ever since, by controlling each movement through the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it turns out, as it happens now, that even the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and turns circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the revenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be sustained that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
