Climate: the caps of France in their financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French caps have been exposed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $3 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has committed to EUR 7,200 million in three years and France EUR 1,260 million (i.e. 420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press wheel, a large complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparent operation was an appreciable result and was truly appreciated: developing countries and civil society wanted all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, there has been no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference in 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years is added to fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with regard to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even diminish), while it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, believe that each euro lent is equivalent to a given euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it turns out that a euro that is to be recovered is going to be equivalent to a euro that is given... As much as it should only be calculated for its commitments the cost of the loan to the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent to a type of interest).
But France does not find such reasoning helpful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); see the EU document to see it for yourself.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among other things, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union gives a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only gives 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only €36.1 million, it can give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional" as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been involved in arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to give when they could simply lend?) and in the negotiations, as developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a short-term one in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be a grain of more sand in the huge machinery that is the CNUC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with a view to respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could make the debate on long-term financing bets progress (another key chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore hope that the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprising announcement on the rapid start of France and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in negotiations.
